   "title": "Man and Woman",
   "year": 1921,
   "image": {
    "file": "File:Man and Woman by Fernand Leger.jpg",
    "thumb640": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Man_and_Woman_by_Fernand_Leger.jpg/960px-Man_and_Woman_by_Fernand_Leger.jpg",
    "thumb1600": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e5/Man_and_Woman_by_Fernand_Leger.jpg",
    "pxW": 1072,
    "pxH": 1516
   },
   "cm": null,
   "collection": "Q1117704",
   "story": {
    "extract": "Man and Woman is an oil-on-canvas painting executed in 1921 by the French artist Fernand Léger. The painting is a cubist portrait of a man and a woman locked in a passionate embrace at odds with their depersonalized, industrialized setting. The painting is held by the Indianapolis Museum of Art, United States.",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_and_Woman_%28L%C3%A9ger%29"
   },
   "facts": [
    {
     "text": "Léger rejected many aspects of cubism, such as multiple simultaneous vantage points, but retained the trait of reducing figures to their most basic, geometric components. To that end, the woman in this painting consists of curves and the color orange, while the man is depicted in columns and blue.",
     "section": "Description",
     "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_and_Woman_%28L%C3%A9ger%29#Description"
    },
    {
     "text": "Léger's battlefront experiences during World War I instilled in him the conviction that art should reflect the new, mechanized world, and be accessible to the average person. He identified strongly with the working class.",
     "section": "Historical information",
     "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_and_Woman_%28L%C3%A9ger%29#Historical_information"
    },
    {
     "text": "Man and Woman was acquired by the IMA in 1952, courtesy of the Martha Delzell Memorial Fund. It has the acquisition number 52.28.",
     "section": "Acquisition",
     "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man_and_Woman_%28L%C3%A9ger%29#Acquisition"
    }
   ],
   "license": {
    "name": "Public domain",
    "credit": "Fernand Léger"
   }
